PART 2 — PKI (Public Key Infrastructure)

This is probably the most important topic in this block.


---

The Problem

Suppose you open:

https://barclays.com

Question:

How do you know it's really Barclays?

Maybe attacker created:

barclays-secure-login.com

Looks identical.


---

PKI Solves Trust

Think:

PKI
=
Trust Framework

PKI allows computers to verify identities.


---

Components of PKI

Remember these.


---

Certificate Authority (CA)

Trusted organization.

Examples:

DigiCert

GlobalSign


Their job:

Verify identities.

Issue certificates.


---

Certificate

Digital identity card.

Contains:

Organization Name

Public Key

Expiration Date

CA Signature



---

Private Key

Secret.

Owned by organization.

Never shared.


---

Real-Life Analogy

Passport System.


---

Government:

Certificate Authority.


---

Passport:

Certificate.


---

Person:

Certificate Owner.


---

Browser trusts certificate because it trusts the CA.


---

Banking Example

Customer visits:

https://barclays.com

Barclays sends certificate.

Browser asks:

Is certificate valid?

Has it expired?

Is CA trusted?

Has certificate been revoked?

If yes:

Connection Trusted


---

Validate

Question:

Can anyone create a certificate?

YES.

Question:

Will browser trust it?

NO.

Needs trusted CA.


---

Think Beyond Academics

Question:

What happens if a CA is compromised?

Answer:

Huge trust problem.

Potentially affects many organizations.

This is why PKI is so important.


---

PART 3 — PKI Practical

Now let's see how it works.


---

Step 1

Organization generates:

Public Key
Private Key


---

Step 2

Creates:

Certificate Signing Request
(CSR)


---

Step 3

Sent to CA.


---

Step 4

CA validates organization.


---

Step 5

CA issues certificate.


---

Step 6

Certificate installed on server.


---

Step 7

Customers connect.

Browser validates certificate.


---

Banking Example

When customer sees:

🔒 HTTPS

All these PKI steps happened behind the scenes.


---

Why Certificate Expiry Exists

Question:

Why not issue certificate forever?

Because:

Organizations change

Keys may be compromised

Security standards evolve



---

Real Security Incident Example

Imagine:

Private key stolen.

Organization revokes certificate.

Browsers stop trusting it.

PKI helps limit damage.


